    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1943-12-06T23:59:59-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1943-12-06T00:00:00-05:00" n="492"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d492">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">740.0011 <gloss target="#t_EW1">EW</gloss>
                    1939/32218</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Soviet Ambassador</hi> (<persName corresp="#p_GAA1"
                        type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Gromyko</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#left">
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">confidential</hi>
                    </seg>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1943-12-06">December 6,
                            1943</date>.</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>
                    <hi rend="smallcaps">My Dear Mr. Secretary</hi>: I have the honor to ask you to
                    transmit the following communication from Mr. <persName corresp="#p_MVM1">V. M.
                        Molotov</persName> to Mr. <persName corresp="#p_HHL1">Harry L.
                        Hopkins</persName> in answer to the latter’s telegram addressed to Mr.
                        <persName corresp="#p_MVM1">Molotov</persName>
                    <note n="1" xml:id="d492fn1">
                        <hi rend="italic">Ante</hi>, <ref target="#pg_775">p. 775</ref>.</note> and
                    handed to him by Mr. <persName corresp="#p_HMM1">Hamilton</persName> on December
                    3, 1943.</p>
                <quote rend="blockquote">
                    <p>“Personal and secret to Mr. <persName corresp="#p_HHL1">Harry L.
                            Hopkins</persName> from <persName corresp="#p_MVM1">V. M.
                            Molotov</persName>
                    </p>
                    <p>Just like you I cannot but express my satisfaction regarding our work
                        together at the Teheran Conference and the possibility of continuation of
                        this work in the future.</p>
                    <p>The meeting of Premier <persName corresp="#p_SIV1">Stalin</persName> with
                        President <persName corresp="#p_RFD1">Roosevelt</persName> is of the
                        greatest importance for drawing closer together the peoples of our countries
                        in the interests of the cause of speeding up our common victory and post-war
                        collaboration.</p>
                    <p>Best wishes.”<note n="2" xml:id="d492fn2">The quoted message was transmitted
                            to <persName corresp="#p_HHL1">Hopkins</persName> in a letter from
                                <persName corresp="#p_HC1">Hull</persName>, dated December 10, 1943
                                (<persName corresp="#p_HHL1">Hopkins</persName> Papers).</note>
                    </p>
                </quote>
                <p>Accept [etc.]</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <persName corresp="#p_GAA1">
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">A. Gromyko</hi>
                        </persName>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
